This works if you use any network that is not the default one. We do this for compatibility with Docker, who do not enable DNS on their default network. If you really want to, you can edit the default network we provide and add the following config snippet to enable DNS aliasing:

```
            {
                "capabilities": {
                    "aliases": true
                },
                "domainName": "dns.podman",
                "type": "dnsname"
            }
```

@baude @Luap99 @rhatdan Does restricting DNS on the default network actually make sense? Are there use-cases that actually rely on this *not* working?
